the transfer problem in reducing the us current account deficit stanford center for international development scid jump to navigation scid stanford center for international development search the site enter your keywords home about us research at scid events at scid people at scid scid publications support us contact us the transfer problem in reducing the us current account deficit type scid working paper 326 author s ronald mckinnon published 05 1 07 region general download pdf abstract correcting global trade imbalances is one form of the transfer problem spending must be transferred from trade deficit countries mainly the united states to trade surplus countries reducing the us current account deficit requires that net saving be increased in the united states and reduced abroad especially in asia but contrary to most literature on the subject exchange rates need not and probably best not be changed as part of the transfer process to improve the us trade balance to show why this is so the paper draws on the older literature on the transfer problem associated with paying war reparations adjustment in absorption ie aggregate spending is two sided because the loser the transferor must raise taxes to pay an indemnity to the winner the transferee which then spends it but there is no presumption that the terms of trade must turn against the transferor that is the losing country which is forced into running a trade surplus or smaller deficit need not depreciate its real exchange rate to effect the transfer stanford university economics department stanford institute for economic policy research public policy program contact us
